summaries.title: Summary 301.1
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 1/4]

summaries.title: Summary 301.2
summaries.summaryText: Sarah described bridging mental health awareness into STEM culture through peer-led workshops. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 301.3
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah described how leading senior design teams strengthened her confidence in project management and technical problem-solving. She reflected on mentorship as a core component of her academic identity, often supporting younger women of color navigating engineering culture. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Served as a teaching assistant for an introductory design course, emphasizing peer inclusivity. [Timeline 3]
Co-founded a mentorship initiative within NSBE for first- and second-year engineering students. [Timeline 3]
Completed internship at a manufacturing firm where he recognized gender imbalance in leadership positions. [Timeline 4]
Joined the Engineering Learning Community, finding peer mentors and emotional support. [Timeline 3]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Peer Mentorship as a Belonging Intervention
themes.description: Daniel emphasized how structured mentorship programs provided psychological safety and belonging cues, normalizing struggle and improving persistence among marginalized students. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Imposter Syndrome Among First-Generation Asian-American Students
themes.description: Daniel’s experience illustrates how first-generation students often internalize academic challenges as personal shortcomings, especially when they lack peers with shared backgrounds in STEM programs. [Extended 2]

quotes.quoteText: I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 1]
Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 4]
Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 4]
Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 2]
